  "output": "## Scope note\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper CLI (fetchers → filters → SQLite dedup store → notifiers), not a web app — there's no React/frontend code anywhere in the repo. I've mapped your ask onto the equivalent concerns for this stack: N+1 → SQLite round-trips, re-renders → n/a, caching/memory-leaks/redundant-computation → still fully applicable.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch (often thousands — `sources.yaml` has 132 configured boards, several with `max_pages` up to 40×10 roles), this does one `SELECT` then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` **per job**, all inside a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)   # separate execute()\n    ...\n```\n\nThat's 2–3N round-trips through the sqlite3 driver for a run that fetches N listings. Fix: one batched `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` (chunked for SQLite's host-parameter cap) to build a `{key: content_hash}` lookup, then classify in Python and flush with three `executemany()` calls:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    if not jobs:\n        return [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):          # stay under SQLite's param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        ph = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({ph})\", chunk)\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = job.to_row(); row[\"now\"] = now      # compute key/content_hash ONCE (see #3)\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append(row)\n        elif prev != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append(row)\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n\n    if insert_rows: cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...)\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows: cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title,... WHERE key=:key\", update_rows)\n    if touched:      cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in touched])\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match(job, ...)` once per job, and `match()` recompiles the include/exclude keyword lists **from scratch on every call**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every job\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every job\n```\n\n`re.compile()` isn't cached the way `re.match(str, ...)` is — this is genuinely N×M wasted compiles (N jobs × M keywords) per pipeline run. Fix: compile once outside the loop and pass compiled patterns in:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(and change `match()`'s type hints to `list[re.Pattern]`, dropping the internal `_compile()` calls).\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:55-69` (`Job.key` / `Job.content_hash`)\n\nBoth are plain `@property`s that recompute a string join + SHA-256 hash on **every access**. In the current `diff()`, `job.key` is read for the `SELECT`, `job.content_hash` is read for the comparison, then `_insert`/`_update` call `job.to_row()`, which recomputes both again via `asdict()` — so each new/changed job pays for the hash twice. The batched `diff()` above fixes this incidentally by calling `to_row()` exactly once per job and reusing the dict.\n\n## 4. Missing index — `store.py:127-135` (`added_since`)\n\n`agent.py db-new` (the main scan entry point) runs this on every invocation:\n\n```python\n\"SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\"\n```\n\nThe schema only indexes `company` (store.py:27); `first_seen` has no index, so this is a full table scan + sort on every scan. Add:\n\n```python\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n## 5. Caching / latency — `notify.py:105-109` (`dispatch`)\n\nNotifiers run strictly sequentially, each with its own timeout (`slack`/`webhook`/`email`/`sms` all have independent 15s-ish budgets, plus blocking `smtplib`):\n\n```python\ndef dispatch(new, changed):\n    for fn in NOTIFIERS:\n        fn(new, changed)   # blocks the next one\n```\n\nIf Slack is slow or down, it delays email/SMS by up to its full timeout every run. Since `dispatch()` is called from an already-`async` `pipeline.run()`, fan the sync notifiers out via a thread pool and `asyncio.gather`:\n\n```python\nasync def dispatch_async(new, changed):\n    loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n    async def run_one(fn):\n        try:\n            await loop.run_in_executor(None, fn, new, changed)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n    await asyncio.gather(*(run_one(fn) for fn in NOTIFIERS))\n```\n\n## 6. Secondary: serial pagination when total is known upfront — `fetchers.py`\n\nMost paginators (`fetch_google`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_twosigma`) stop on \"no new results,\" so they can't be trivially parallelized. But `fetch_workday` (:773), `fetch_phenom` (:702) and `fetch_bytedance` (:647) all get a `total`/`totalHits`/`count` back on page 0 — yet still `await` each subsequent page one at a time in a loop. For a large board (Workday tenants with 1000+ postings), that's dozens of serial round-trips that could instead be one page-0 fetch to learn `total`, then `asyncio.gather` over the remaining offsets. Lower priority than 1–5 since it only affects those three ATSs, but worth doing if scan latency matters.\n\n## Memory leaks — none found\n\n`httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:1126) is correctly closed in a `finally` block; `Store` connections are closed via `__exit__`; no growing module-level caches. This is a short-lived CLI process each run, so classic leak patterns don't really apply here.\n",
